          "body": "The chapter’s narrative scenes are anthropological as much as Christological. **Mary** (12:3) represents extravagant worship that pours out value on Christ — a year’s wages on His feet, hair as a towel, prophetic anticipation of His burial. **Judas** (12:4-6) represents calculated hypocrisy — religious-sounding objection masking theft and treachery. **The crowd** (12:13) represents enthusiastic but misreading messianism — the same throats that shout *Hosanna* will shout *crucify*. **The rulers** (12:42-43) represent the most dangerous response — belief without confession, restrained by fear of social cost. John lines these up for the reader’s self-examination. Which response is yours?"
